Explain top down design: 
Top-down design is a programming concept that involves breaking a program into 
smaller parts, using functions. It is particularly helpful when writing a program
 that needs to do multiple things, such as validate input, that build off of each 
 other. For example, if I went to subway to get a footlong sub, and wanted to 
 explain the process to a friend who didn't understand how ordering a sub worked, 
 I wouldn't just dump all of the information and steps into one run on sentence. 
 Using the different steps of sub creation, such as bread selection, decision to 
 heat, meat selection, topping selection, and sauce selection, I'd describe each part
 as its own function, and break the explanation into smaller parts, so that the 
 listener can better understand how each part works and functions as a part of the
 whole. This isn't necessarily needed in every program, and for simpler programs, 
 such specific segmentation might actually overcomplicate things, but for example our
 assignment this week, breaking down the functions of a multiplication table 
 program, makes it much easier to understand and tweak any errors or issues in the 
 parts of the program.
